communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Police Settlements (Anaheim City Attorney)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Copies of all reports, lists, databases, or individual documents created since 1/1/16 detail lawsuits brought against the city's police department. This should include any documentation mechanism your department uses to track lawsuits. It should also include any documents your department submits to local, state, or federal agencies listing the number and/or status of lawsuits brought against the police department.

This request should be construed to include documents compiled quarterly, annually, or in other increments as well as documents or databases that contain responsive information over a longer time span.

Please provide all available materials from January 1, 2016 through November 6, 2024.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

Please note that the APD has no document(s) that identify the exact compilation of information that you have requested and has no duty to create a record that does not exist at the time of the request. [Haynie v. Superior Court (2001) 26 Cal.4th 1061; 71 Ops.CalAtty.Gen. 235 (1988)]. Certain records that may be responsive to your request may be withheld from production or redacted pursuant to various exemptions to the Public Records Act including the pursuant to various exemptions to the Public Records Act including the following: • The records may be subject to the public interest exemption (Gov. Code § 7922.000); • The records may be subject to the peace officer privilege and protections provided by Penal Code §§ 832.7 and 832.8(a)(1)-(6) and Evidence Code §§ 1040-1045; • The records may consist of notes and/or drafts (Gov. Code, §7927.500); and/or • Personnel files are exempt from disclosure (Gov. Code §7927.7000). Without waiving, and subject to, the foregoing objections, the APD has identified records responsive to your request. Copies of those records are available within this portal. Thank you. * SKM_C750i24120215210.pdf ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? title: Police Rosters + Photos (Beverly Hills Police Department)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Police Rosters + Photos (Beverly Hills Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Hello, 

The roster of sworn police officers from 2016 - 2024
Names, badge numbers, serial numbers, division/station, sworn status.

 The department's headshot photos of all of the same officers are referenced above. Duplicates from each year do not need to be completed. At a minimum, photos for 2023 - 2024 should be included. 

Precedent: Santa Ana Police Department and LAPD have released their photos. A reminder that nothing in California Penal Code 832.7 mentions photographs in personnel records are kept confidential. Not only that, but videos and pictures of officers are regularly shared on social media. 
https://www.courthousenews.com/judge-tosses-las-second-lawsuit-against-journalist-over-police-headshots/
https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-11-13/city-of-la-officers-city

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

communications.subject: RE: California Public Records Act Request #CRM-24-2347
communications.communication:
Dear Mr. Scott, The City of Beverly Hills is in receipt of your request for public records pursuant to the California Public Records Act (Government Code section 7920.000 et seq.), dated and received by the City on December 5, 2024. Pursuant to Government Code Section 7922.535, this letter serves as the City’s written response and notice that due to unusual circumstances, an extension of the initial statutory 10-day determination period was reasonably necessary for the proper processing of your request. Specifically, there remains a need to search for, collect, and appropriately examine a voluminous amount of separate and distinct records that are demanded by your request. The City has identified responsive records and is still in the process of retrieving and reviewing other potentially responsive records. The City anticipates making a first production of responsive records by Friday, January 10, 2025. Please be advised that the City will be withholding information regarding specific officers pursuant to Government Code section 7922.000 because of undercover or security-sensitive assignments and a particularized threat of harm. Thank you, The Beverly Hills City Clerk’s Office 

This email is in reference to issue CRM-24-2347 (CRM-pE0gW9qGQ). In case of any queries, you can respond to this email and we will get back to you as soon as we can.

Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee

Renee

title: SNOHOMISH SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: SNOHOMISH SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
January 12, 2025

via email to publicrecords@sno.wednet.edu

SNOHOMISH SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
 
To whom it may concern,

RCW 40.14.026(5)

“To improve best practices for dissemination of public records, each agency with actual staff and legal costs associated with fulfilling public records requests of at least one hundred thousand dollars during the prior fiscal year must… report to the joint legislative audit and review committee by July 1st of each subsequent year the following metrics, measured over the preceding year:

RCW 40.14.026(5)(l)

(l) The estimated costs incurred by the agency in fulfilling records requests, including costs for staff compensation and legal review, and a measure of the average cost per request;

RCW 40.14.026(5)(o)

(o) The costs incurred by the agency with managing and retaining records, including staff compensation and purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests;

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

1. Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024.

Responsive public records should include but are not limited to:

Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in the numerical order requested by subject matter and year. The most recent public records should be produced first.

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

The use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA or NEXTREQUEST) for communication and production of records in response to a public records request is optional for the requestor in the State of Washington. Respectfully we decline to use any 3rd party "portal" system, specifically GOVQA and NEXTREQUEST. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment, or via no password, no registration internet cloud-based download link.

Please do not direct or invite us to use, register for, or communicate with your agency via any 3rd party portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other commercial 3rd party records portal service.

Constructive Notice: Any and all communication(s) received on behalf of your agency in reference to this Public Records Request (RCW 42.45) from any unauthorized for-profit 3rd party company doing business outside the State of Washington will be the subject of a new public records request to your agency as to the origin and purpose of the communication as well as the identity of the sender of the communication.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format. Unless the records exist IN PAPER FORM ONLY, DO NOT instead create new records by printing native stored electronic files, then scanning and re-printing these newly scanned prints only to reproduce them in again in electronic production.

EMAIL RECORDS

Please provide any and all email records in NATIVE .pst electronic format.

FEES

In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION - FAMILY EDUCATIONAL RIGHTS AND PRIVACY ACT (FERPA)

Take caution with the broad application of redaction and withholding of identified public records claiming "global FERPA" exemptions. When an agency claims an exemption for an entire record or portion of one, it must inform the requestor of the statutory exemption and provide a brief explanation of how the exemption applies to the record or portion withheld. RCW 42.17.310(4)/42.56.210(3). The brief explanation should cite the statute the agency claims grant an exemption from disclosure. The brief explanation should provide enough information for a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the claimed exemption is proper. Global, nonspecific claims of exemption such as "FERPA" are insufficient. One way to properly provide a brief explanation of the withheld record or redaction is for the agency to provide a withholding index. It identifies the type of record, its date and number of pages, and the author or recipient of the record (unless their identity is exempt). The withholding index should allow a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the agency has properly invoked the exemption. There are several exceptions to the FERPA exemption and any agency silently withholding large swaths of public records citing "FERPA!" without providing the original identified record, properly redacted, or if withheld in its entirety, providing a record description and page count or record length, will be challenged in accordance with RCW 42.56.550 if a reasonably detailed withholding index or exemption log is not included.

EXEMPTION LOGS

Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION

The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request: SNOHOMISH SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

I wanted to follow up on the following Washington Public Records Act request, copied below, and originally submitted on Jan. 13, 2025. Please let me know when I can expect to receive a response.

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

Dear MuckRock Requestor,

On January 13, 2025, the Snohomish School District received your request for the following: 

Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024. Responsive public records should include but are not limited to: Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection. 

In compliance with the agency response window of five business days that is outlined in RCW 42.56.520, your records are now ready. 

These records contain redacted information. In accordance with RCW 42.56.070(1), a description of the redactions and exemptions utilized is included with each record.

Since the cost of these records is negligible, we have uploaded them at no charge to the MuckRock portal you provided. 

Pursuant to RCW 42.56.550, the statute of limitations has begun to run, and any judicial review of the district’s actions taken or challenged must be filed within one year of today’s date, January 17, 2025. 

This completes your records request.

Snohomish School District 
1601 Avenue D
Snohomish, WA 98290 
PH: 360-563-7328

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request: SNOHOMISH SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
Dear MuckRock Requestor,

On January 13, 2025, the Snohomish School District received your request for the following:

Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024. Responsive public records should include but are not limited to: Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection.

In compliance with the agency response window of five business days that is outlined in RCW 42.56.520, your records are now ready.

These records contain redacted information. In accordance with RCW 42.56.070(1), a description of the redactions and exemptions utilized is included with each record.

Since the cost of these records is negligible, we have uploaded them at no charge to the MuckRock portal you provided.

Pursuant to RCW 42.56.550, the statute of limitations has begun to run, and any judicial review of the district’s actions taken or challenged must be filed within one year of today’s date, January 17, 2025.

This completes your records request.

Snohomish School District
1601 Avenue D
Snohomish, WA 98290
PH: 360-563-7328

communications.subject: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Miami-Dade police disciplinary files
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Florida Sunshine Law, I hereby request the following records:

- Any and all lists, spreadsheets or other organized datasets that detail potential or substantiated allegations of misconduct and/or impeached or impeachable testimony, created under Brady v. Maryland and/or Giglio v. United States.
- Any and all records regarding substantiated allegations of misconduct or violations of internal department policy or criminal law by specific law enforcement officers.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

communications.subject: RE: Florida Sunshine Law Request: Miami-Dade police disciplinary files
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

As to you first request: While we maintain a Brady list, our list consists of pending investigations known to the officers as well as the pending charges against the officers, which are considered Brady by law.  See attached.
As to your second request: We do not track such information, as such we have no responsive public records.
Lastly, as an aside, unlike other jurisdictions, in Florida pursuant to Chapter 119, F.S., closed police disciplinary investigative files are a matter of public record and are available from individual employing police agencies.

title: RENTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: RENTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
January 12, 2025

via email to public.records@rentonschools.us

RENTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
 
To whom it may concern,

RCW 40.14.026(5)

“To improve best practices for dissemination of public records, each agency with actual staff and legal costs associated with fulfilling public records requests of at least one hundred thousand dollars during the prior fiscal year must… report to the joint legislative audit and review committee by July 1st of each subsequent year the following metrics, measured over the preceding year:

RCW 40.14.026(5)(l)

(l) The estimated costs incurred by the agency in fulfilling records requests, including costs for staff compensation and legal review, and a measure of the average cost per request;

RCW 40.14.026(5)(o)

(o) The costs incurred by the agency with managing and retaining records, including staff compensation and purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests;

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST RCW 42.56

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act [RCW 42.56] I hereby request the following records:

1. Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted fee payments paid to your agency in 2024.

Responsive public records should include but are not limited to:

Supplies and services external services (e.g., printing services, large format printing) Mailing costs, supplies (CDs, DVDs, USB sticks, etc.) Staff compensation and benefit records, copies of payments of Public Records Fees Collected, Software licensing, public records portal and database software licensing and costs, purchases of equipment, hardware, software, and services to manage and retain public records or otherwise assist in the fulfillment of public records requests, professional services Agency staff costs, copies of billing for all Legal costs – including copies of all litigation Legal settlements related to public records requests litigation of any kind and copies of costs for staff time associated with invoicing and collection.

RECORDS INSTALLMENTS

If production of responsive records will be completed in multiple installments, please begin by producing records in the numerical order requested by subject matter and year. The most recent public records should be produced first.

DEFINITION OF RECORDS AND WRITINGS

RECORDS AND WRITINGS as defined by RCW 42.56.010(4): any handwriting, typewriting, printing, photostating, photographing, and every other means of recording any form of communication or representation including, but not limited to, letters, words, pictures, sounds, or symbols, or combination thereof, and all papers, maps, magnetic or paper tapes, photographic films and prints, motion picture, film and video recordings, magnetic or punched cards, discs, drums, diskettes, sound recordings, and other documents including existing data compilations from which information may be obtained or translated.

PRODUCTION AND DELIVERY OF ELECTRONIC RECORDS

Please provide all records in their native electronic format. Please do not instead create new records by printing electronic files then scanning and printing the newly scanned prints.

The use of 3rd party “portals” (Such as GOVQA or NEXTREQUEST) for communication and production of records in response to a public records request is optional for the requestor in the State of Washington. Respectfully we decline to use any 3rd party "portal" system, specifically GOVQA and NEXTREQUEST. Please provide all records electronically via direct email attachment, or via no password, no registration internet cloud-based download link.

Please do not direct or invite us to use, register for, or communicate with your agency via any 3rd party portal including but not limited to FOIAOnline, GovQA, NextRequest, FOIAExpress, JustFOIA FOIADirect, WebForm, or any other commercial 3rd party records portal service.

Constructive Notice: Any and all communication(s) received on behalf of your agency in reference to this Public Records Request (RCW 42.45) from any unauthorized for-profit 3rd party company doing business outside the State of Washington will be the subject of a new public records request to your agency as to the origin and purpose of the communication as well as the identity of the sender of the communication.

PUBLIC RECORDS REQUESTS SUBMITTED VIA EMAIL

RCW 42.56.080 - Identifiable records—Facilities for copying—Availability of public records.

"...Agencies shall honor requests received in person during an agency's normal office hours, or by mail or email, for identifiable public records unless exempted by provisions of this chapter. No official format is required for making a records request; however, agencies may recommend that requestors submit requests using an agency provided form or web page."

This public records request is being made via email. This public records request will be honored and fulfilled by your agency via email as requested or relief will be sought per statute.

NATIVE ELECTRONIC FORMAT

Please provide all identified public records in their NATIVE electronic format. Unless the records exist IN PAPER FORM ONLY, DO NOT instead create new records by printing native stored electronic files, then scanning and re-printing these newly scanned prints only to reproduce them in again in electronic production.

EMAIL RECORDS

Please provide any and all email records in NATIVE .pst electronic format.

FEES

In the event that there are fees, please inform us of the total charges in advance of fulfilling the request in strict compliance with all provisions of the Washington State Public Records Act.

EXEMPTION - FAMILY EDUCATIONAL RIGHTS AND PRIVACY ACT (FERPA)

Take caution with the broad application of redaction and withholding of identified public records claiming "global FERPA" exemptions. When an agency claims an exemption for an entire record or portion of one, it must inform the requestor of the statutory exemption and provide a brief explanation of how the exemption applies to the record or portion withheld. RCW 42.17.310(4)/42.56.210(3). The brief explanation should cite the statute the agency claims grant an exemption from disclosure. The brief explanation should provide enough information for a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the claimed exemption is proper. Global, nonspecific claims of exemption such as "FERPA" are insufficient. One way to properly provide a brief explanation of the withheld record or redaction is for the agency to provide a withholding index. It identifies the type of record, its date and number of pages, and the author or recipient of the record (unless their identity is exempt). The withholding index should allow a requestor to make a threshold determination of whether the agency has properly invoked the exemption. There are several exceptions to the FERPA exemption and any agency silently withholding large swaths of public records citing "FERPA!" without providing the original identified record, properly redacted, or if withheld in its entirety, providing a record description and page count or record length, will be challenged in accordance with RCW 42.56.550 if a reasonably detailed withholding index or exemption log is not included.

EXEMPTION LOGS

Please ensure all redactions or exemptions claimed by your agency in the production of responsive records are accompanied by a complete and detailed exemption log noting the valid legal reason for each exemption at each redaction location in the record produced, as well as the specific number of pages if any that your agency redacts or withholds in their entirety. Each redaction should be noted by footnote or by a clear reference to the specific justification for that redaction, and only the minimal exempt portion of any record may be withheld.

COMMERCIAL PURPOSE DECLARATION

The Washington State Public Records Act prohibits the disclosure of “lists of individuals” for a commercial purpose (RCW 42.56.070(8)). I declare this public records request is not being made for any commercial purpose whatsoever. Also, this public records request is not being made for a "list of individuals." This declaration satisfies all requirements of RCW 42.56 regarding prohibitions on lists and commercial purposes. No additional commercial purpose declaration will be completed for this public records request.

COMMUNICATION VIA EMAIL

Please send all requests for clarification, status updates, and production of responsive electronic documents via direct email.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. We look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Good Luck.

communications.subject: Re: Washington Public Records Act Request: RENTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - JLARC (2024) Agency Costs Fulfilling Public Records Requests Including Litigation for the year 2024
communications.communication:
January 17, 2025

Re: January 13, 2025, Public Records Act Request

 179616-45457741@requests.muckrock.com,

This letter constitutes Renton School District’s response to your January 13, 2025, request for records pursuant to the Washington State Public Records Act (“PRA”) RCW 42.56. The District has reproduced your request below for reference:

Please provide all "Public Records" (as defined by WAC 44-14-03001) detailing costs incurred by your agency in fulfilling records requests, including staff compensation, legal review, and any public records related litigation costs and/or legal settlements for the year 2024 and complete copies of all records request realted (sic) fee payments paid to your agency in 2024.

Based upon the foregoing request, the district hereby encloses the documents responsive to your request subject to public disclosure. Please note the district has not typically met the threshold for reporting to JLARC. The district also did not collect fees for records requests in 2024. The district believes the records provided are fully responsive to your request as the district has interpreted it. Therefore, the district now considers your request to be fully satisfied and closed as of today’s date without any further action. Pursuant to RCW 42.56.550, any judicial review of the district’s actions taken or challenged must be filed within one year of today’s date January 17, 2025.

Please be advised that to the extent that the District inadvertently produces any privileged document(s) that are encompassed by an exemption under the PRA, or any applicable state or federal law, such production is not intended to be a waiver of any privilege or any right to withhold such documents or documents of a similar nature.

Should you have any questions or need to clarify your request(s), please do not hesitate to contact me public.records@rentonschools.us<mailto:public.records@rentonschools.us> so we can work together to resolve any issues.

Sincerely,

Public Records

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to DoD for list of all 2024 movie collaborations
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A list of all the films that the Department of Defense has participated in the production of, in any capacity whatsoever, for the year 2024. Any and all such lists, full or partial, would be appreciated and may include, but are not limited to, entertainment liaison (ELO) reports or similar internal documents. I request that you search for these documents in any location where they might be located, including but not limited to the entertainment liaison offices, public affairs offices, and communications HQ.

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation as well as the editor-in-chief and a contributor to a research magazine published by said foundation titled "Cultural Engineering Studies." These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

title: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Office of Government Information Services)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Office of Government Information Services)
communications.communication:
Dear Office of Government Information Services,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to Office of Government Information Services's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Sai
President, Fiat Fiendum, Inc.

P.S. Sai is my full legal name.

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into Maurice Hubert Stans (March 22, 1908 - April 14, 1998). Proof of death is not required as his date of birth was over 100 years ago.

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records for all relevant names, individuals, agencies and companies at FBI Headquarters. Please also conduct a search for records at the Alexandria Records Center. If any potentially responsive records have been destroyed and/or transferred to NARA, then I request copies of the destruction or transfer slips as well as any other documentation relating to, mentioning or describing said transfer or destruction, to include but not be limited to confirmation that the Bureau has no other copies of said records. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Galante

title: Obama Library: WHTV Tapes of July 7th, 2009 Visit To Moscow, Russia

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Obama Library: WHTV Tapes of July 7th, 2009 Visit To Moscow, Russia
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

White House Communications Agency video footage (WHTV content) filmed during President Obama's July 7th, 2009 visit to Moscow, Russia. On that day Obama gave remarks at The New Economic School in Moscow. He also had a photo opportunity with then-Prime Minister Putin, as well as televised remarks with President Medvedev and a meeting with opposition leaders as well as remarks at a parallel business and civil society summit. 

This is a request to review all footage from that day, including outtakes and rushes. 

The President's visit to Moscow is described on these pages:

https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-new-economic-school-graduation
https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-obama-and-prime-minister-putin-russia-meeting
https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-obama-and-president-medvedev-russia-meeting
https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-obama-meeting-with-opposition-leaders
https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-parallel-business-summit
https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/remarks-president-parallel-civil-society-summit

It would be wonderful if these could be uploaded to the Obama Presidential Library YouTube page: https://www.youtube.com/@obamalibrary - As other similar requests have been.

Thank you for the Obama Presidential Library's commitment to transparency, and I look forward to the resolution of this request.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Robert Delaware

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Request: James Earl Ray
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act.  I hereby request the following records:

James Earl Ray (March 10, 1928 – April 23, 1998) was an American convicted of the assassination of civil rights leader Martin Luther King, Jr. Ray was convicted on his 41st birthday after entering a guilty plea to forgo a jury trial. Had he been found guilty by jury trial, he would have been eligible for the death penalty. He was sentenced to 99 years in prison. He later recanted his confession and tried unsuccessfully to gain access to a retrial. In 1998, Ray died in prison of complications due to chronic hepatitis C infection. His death has been widely reported. http://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/24/us/james-earl-ray-70-killer-of-dr-king-dies-in-nashville.html?pagewanted=all

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records.

I am a member of the news media and request classification as such.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.


Sincerely,

Michael Best

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: 2024 Texas Body Camera Awards
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

On December 18, 2024 Governor Abbott announced that the Public Safety Office will administer over $500 million in grant funding for a variety of public safety programs and services in Texas, including 98 awards, totaling $4.6 million, to equip peace officers with body-worn camera systems.  Please provide a list of those agencies receiving body-worn camera awards, showing the amounts awarded to each agency (if available).  If a list of the awardees does not exist, please provide any documents, reports, data files, or communications that identify the body-worn camera award recipients.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Paul Tepper

title: Purchases by Delaware under the 1122 Program (Department of Safety and Homeland Security)

communications.subject: Delaware Freedom of Information Act Request: Purchases by Delaware under the 1122 Program (Department of Safety and Homeland Security)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Delaware Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

-An itemized list of all purchases of equipment by law enforcement agencies (LEAs) through the 1122 program (10 U.S. Code § 281) from 1994 to 2024. This can be provided by annual purchase requests that are sent to the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) by the state point of contact (SPOC). This can also be provided by collated receipts for purchases by the agencies.

-All 1122C: Usage Reports and purchase orders submitted by LEAs to the SPOC. According to the 1122 Program Guide, 1122C: Usage Reports and purchase orders are required to be sent to the SPOC within 30 days of purchase.

-DA Report: total expenditures to the Department of the Army which are reported annually and are releasable. The requested date range of the requested annual reports is 1994 to 2024.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Rudenberg, a citizen of Delaware, in coordination with Lillian Mauldin.

communications.subject: FOIA Request from Jonathan Rudenberg
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

By email, you made a request under the Delaware Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) for,  "An itemized list of all purchases of equipment by law enforcement agencies (LEAs) through the 1122 program (10 U.S. Code § 281) from 1994 to 2024. This can be provided by annual purchase requests that are sent to the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) by the state point of contact (SPOC). This can also be provided by collated receipts for purchases by the agencies.  All 1122C: Usage Reports and purchase orders submitted by LEAs to the SPOC. According to the 1122 Program Guide, 1122C: Usage Reports and purchase orders are required to be sent to the SPOC within 30 days of purchase. DA Report: total expenditures to the Department of the Army which are reported annually and are releasable. The requested date range of the requested annual reports is 1994 to 2024.."

Please note that FOIA allows access to "public records," unless the public record requested falls within one of the enumerated statutory exemptions. See 29 Del. C. §10002 (definition of "public record" and specific exemptions); 29 Del. C. § 10003 (setting forth FOIA request procedures).

The Department of Safety and Homeland Security (DSHS) has reviewed your FOIA request, and I have attached (three) the responsive records. Additionally, information that is already public is not subject to FOIA.  Please see these public web sites which contains information related to your request.   Any equipment that has been transferred would be available via the LESO website at https://www.dla.mil/Disposition-Services/Offers/Law-Enforcement/Public-Information/.  Additional information is available at https://www.dla.mil/Portals/104/Documents/DispositionServices/LESO/AllStatesAndTerritories_04012024.xlsx?ver=FILIC7hUfEGsazc97C9dbA%3d%3d.

The DSHS considers your request closed.

Hello,

Thank you for your response. It appears that this data is for the 1033 Program, which a free of cost (except for shipping costs) transfer program. As mentioned in my request, I am seeking data on purchases made through the 1122 Program, which requires agencies to pay for equipment using a federal discount. Please let me know if Delaware participates in the 1122 Program and where I can obtain data on these purchases.

Lillian Mauldin

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Beverage Agreements
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Agreements related to the beverage pouring, distribution, sales or marketing rights for campus, athletics venues or facilities.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kelly North

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Beverage Agreements (24-399)
communications.communication:
Ms. North—

This is in response to your September 5, 2024, request for documents under the Georgia Open Records Act, and is in accordance with the three-day period of response pursuant to O.C.G.A. § 50-18-71(b)(2).

You have requested “Agreements related to the beverage pouring, distribution, sales or marketing rights for campus, athletics venues or facilities.”

With respect to the portion of your request that deals with the institution, the Georgia Open Records Act allows charges for search, retrieval, review, redaction, and production in connection with compliance; provided, however, that no charge is made for the first quarter-hour. Our search, retrieval, review, redaction, and production charges in complying with this request will be three (3) hours for a total estimate of $137.50 and will require 15 business days for production. The Act also allows for an agency to defer search and retrieval of records until the requester agrees to pay the estimated costs. We ask that you provide confirmation, in writing, to us that you agree to pay these estimated charges.

Because a portion of your request is for records of the University’s intercollegiate sports program, I have forwarded it to the University’s Athletic Department for an assessment of the scope of potentially responsive documents, estimation of the costs to search for and produce responsive records, and consideration of potentially applicable exemptions. A written response to this portion of your request will arrive within the time-period specified in O.C.G.A. § 50-18-71(d.1).

Please let us know how you would like to proceed with the institution portion of your request.


UGA Open Records
Division of Marketing & Communications
Hodgson Oil Building, Suite 200 N | 286 Oconee St. | Athens, GA 30602
706-542-8090 | www.uga.edu<http://www.uga.edu/>
[University of Georgia]

communications.subject: RE: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Beverage Agreements (24-399)
communications.communication:
Ms. North-

This is a follow-up to your Dec. 10 email in which you asked for an update. To reiterate, we produced responsive material Oct. 14 for the institution side of your request. The remainder of your request is regarding material from the UGA Athletic Association. I can reiterate that, as we reported Sept. 10, we forwarded your request to the UGA Athletic Association for an assessment of the scope of potentially responsive documents, estimation of the costs to search for and produce responsive records, and consideration of potentially applicable exemptions. A written response to this portion of your request will arrive within the time-period specified in O.C.G.A. § 50-18-71(d.1).

This portion of the Georgia Code states, "Any other provision of this Code section to the contrary notwithstanding, the period within which any production, access, response, or notice is required from an agency with respect to a request for records, other than salary information for non-clerical staff, of intercollegiate sports programs of any unit of the University System of Georgia, including athletic departments and related private athletic associations, shall be 90 business days from the date the agency received the request."

Specific to your request, 90-business days from your initial request is January 16, 2025.


UGA Open Records
Division of Marketing & Communications
Hodgson Oil Building, Suite 200 N | 286 Oconee St. | Athens, GA 30602
706-542-8090 | www.uga.edu<http://www.uga.edu/>

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Property Records - 299 and 300 Harris Lane
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

For the multifamily property located at 299 and 300 Harris Lane Gallatin TN 37066, please provide the following information: notice and summary of any open zoning, building, and/or fire code violations or written confirmation that none currently exist; copies of Certificates of Occupancy, or if none are available, please state the reason for their absence and whether the lack of Certificates of Occupancy will result in any enforcement action; and copies of any zoning approval documents, such as approved site plans, conditions of approval, variances, special/conditional use permits, etc. if applicable.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Kent Hoover, a citizen of Tennessee, in coordination with Olivia James.

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #24-260
communications.communication:
Hi Stephen,

Hope you enjoyed your new year! Can you please help me understand why this request keeps being delayed? Since this request was opened in July of last year, the estimated completion date has been updated three times.

Thank you,
Rose

communications.subject: RE: Washington Public Records Act Request #24-260
communications.communication:
Hello Rose,

I am happy to attempt to provide clarification regarding this request. SCORE has not yet provided an estimated completion date for this request, however we have provided regular updates since the initial request. The scope of the request required detailed searches to ensure all responsive records were located to best fulfill the request. Once records were located, it was necessary to review the records for any applicable redactions or withholdings. At this time, SCORE believes that all searches have been completed and anticipates that this review will be completed by January 16, 2025, which is why the most recent follow up was provided today, January 2, 2025.

Sincerely,

Stephen Kitajo

communications.subject: North Carolina Public Records Law Request: Mark Mambula report
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the North Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

-OCSO incident report #2017006215 pertaining to the 15Apr17 death of V/MAMBULAO
-all publicly available investigative and police reports pertaining to the aforementioned death

I'm requesting these documents as part of a story for WIRED magazine about the opioid crisis.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Benoit Morenne

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Tom Chris Korologos (April 6, 1933 – July 26, 2024)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records mentioning, relating to, or generated as a result of investigation or inquiry into Republican political adviser and ambassador Tom Chris Korologos (April 6, 1933 – July 26, 2024). His death is widely-known and widely reported; as such, privacy concerns under FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7 are voided, as are any concerns under the Privacy Act. For example, you may find his New York Times obituary at the following link: https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/07/us/politics/tom-korologos-dead.html

Please conduct a search of the Central Records System, including but not limited to the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Indices, the Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) Indices, the Physical Surveillance (FISUR) Indices, and the Technical Surveillance (TESUR) Indices, for both main-file records and cross-reference records of both HQ and all field offices for all relevant names, agencies, organizations, companies and events including but not limited to those cited in the previous paragraphs and/or links as well as a cross-reference with the Southern Poverty Law Center to include any information provided by the SPLC. My request includes but is not limited to 137, 157, 176, 177, 183, 184, 188, and 214 files. If previously released records are available, then I request a rolling release consisting of those records while additional records are located and processed for release.

If any part of these documents are exempt from disclosure, please be sure to review and release all reasonably segregable nonexempt portions of responsive documents, as the FOIA requires.

I request that I be properly classified as a media requester. I am an assistant editor at Reason Magazine who has written numerous articles on topics of public interest, and I am requesting these documents in an editorial capacity. Please contact me if you have any questions about my media status.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Matthew Petti

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Layla the Mighty Minter
communications.communication:
Dear U.S. Mint:

This is a request for records under the Freedom of Information Act. I am requesting records related to the U.S. Mint's mascot, Layla the Mighty Minter.

RECORDS REQUESTED:

(A) All records related to the conception of and process of designing the Layla mascot (emails and other correspondence, memoranda, contracts, sketches, etc.)

(B) Records sufficient to answer the following questions:

(1) Whose idea was it to create an U.S. Mint mascot in the first place, and why?

(2) Who designed the Layla mascot, and what was the design process like? (e.g. were there multiple design concepts submitted? Was the design of the character contracted out? (If so, kindly produce the contract).

(3) Were any Layla-related promotional items or tchotchkes created (e.g. trading cards, CDs, coloring books)? If so, please produce them.

(4) Were there any life-size Layla costumes created? If so, please produce records related to the design of the costume (contracts, sketches, etc.) and any guidelines regarding the use of or care for the costume.

(5) Did anyone in Congress ever object to the U.S. Mint's use of a mascot? I understand that there have been periodic attempts by lawmakers (e.g. former Oklahoma senator Tom Coburn, current Iowa senator Jodi Ernst) to rein in agency spending on mascots. If so, please produce all records related to that.

(6) What has the public's reaction been to the Layla mascot?

(7) Is the Mint still using Layla as part of its public outreach? If not, why not?

REQUEST FOR FEE WAIVER:

The requested documents will be made available to the general public online for free, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes. I am working on a project examining the history, creation, evolution, and use of mascots across the federal government—because, like many others, I find them fascinating and weirdly delightful. Thus, I respectfully request that any fees related to this request be waived. If you do decide to charge me fees, please notify me in advance if you expect those fees to exceed $25.

FORM OF PRODUCTION:

I would prefer that this request be filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

CONCLUSION:

Thank you very much for your cooperation with this request. I look forward to hearing from you soon!

Sincerely,

Nicholas Marritz

communications.subject: Reaching out
communications.communication:
Off the record, please, not for publication:

Dear Mr. Marritz,

Not sure if this email will reach you, but wanted to contact you after seeing your name and email listed on a FOIA request regarding US Mint mascots.

I'm following up on Senator Ernst's previous work highlighting mascots at the US Mint, and wanted to thank you for doggedly (or should I say DOGE'edly) pursuing an answer from them!

We had not seen these documents before I came across them, and your work, today.

Would love to chat with you about your work, and any other FOIA's you've been involved in that might help us draw attention to wasteful government spending.

Thanks,
Sheila

Sheila Cole
Office of Senator Joni Ernst (R-IA)
Sheila_Cole@ernst.senate.gov





Mr. Nicholas Marritz
MuckRock News, DEPT MR134412, 263 Huntington
11 Dupont Circle, N.W., Suite 400

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Selective Service System)
communications.communication:
Dear Selective Service System,

On behalf of myself and Fiat Fiendum, I hereby request the following records:

1. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email inbox or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
2. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's email spam folder or equivalent which was received nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
3. The one email in your chief FOIA officer's sent email folder or equivalent which was sent nearest and before October 19, 2024, midnight Eastern time, regardless of subject matter.
4. The total full-time equivalent count of people who work for your FOIA office as of October 19, 2024.

This request is expressly limited to Selective Service System's own FOIA office. Please do not refer it to any other agency or division. This request is expressly not a Privacy Act request, and no PA waiver will be provided.

Please provide the email records in EML, Maildir, MBOX, MIX, MSG, or PST format only — not PDF, Word, image, etc — including all metadata (e.g. full email headers as received/sent) and attachments, without alteration other than narrowly tailored electronic redaction of specifically claimed exemptions that do not affect any part of non exempt information (and, in particular, without rasterization).

Please provide the fourth record as a statement in your response letter, or at your option, as the most readily available record, in original electronic format as currently stored on your computer systems, which includes that information.

Please provide all records either as individual files, or as an unencrypted ZIP file, uploaded to MuckRock. Do not apply any encryption, DRM, or other restriction.

I request fee waiver, because
* Fiat Fiendum is a 501(c)(3) non-profit;
* this request is for public interest, non-commercial purposes;
* these records would give a snapshot of insight into the everyday processes of FOIA offices; and
* these records are being requested in order to conduct a government-wide audit of agencies' FOIA compliance.

In the event that you deny fee waiver, please process this request as-is, because I will not agree to any fees.

Please be sure to provide:
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(II) FOIA Public Liaison information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(aa) appeal information
* 5 USC 552(a)(6)(A)(i)(III)(bb) OGIS information
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(A) tracking number
* 5 USC 552(a)(7)(B)(ii) completion ETA

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Sai
President, Fiat Fiendum, Inc.

P.S. Sai is my full legal name.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request: Chief FOIA officer's recent email (Selective Service System)
communications.communication:
Dear SSS,

Thank you for your extremely quick response. I appeal your search and claim of no records, and your violation of my form and format request.

As for form and format, you stated that you were providing one email, and sent it as a PDF. You did not claim any exemptions.

By exporting it to PDF, you disregarded my electronic form & format requests — and you additionally rasterized the record, which I specifically asked you not to do. OCR does not cure the destruction of the original structural metadata that makes it accessible, nor make available the parts of the records (such as hyperlinks, headers, etc) which were destroyed by rasterization. I did not consent to you making new, worse records in this way.

Please provide the email in one of the native electronic email formats listed; any email software will save to them easily.

My form and format request is mandatory under 5 USC 552(a)(3)(B & C) & (f)(2)(A) (E-FOIA & FOIA Improvement Act) and 29 USC 794d (Rehab Act § 508).


As for your search and claim of no records, I believe you likely searched the "FOIA inbox" account foia@sss.gov. My request was about the chief FOIA officer's emails, i.e. the primary official @sss.gov email used by Craig T. Brown, "regardless of subject matter" — not about FOIA request emails, e.g. not about emails to or from foia@sss.gov. I therefore believe you did not search or provide the records identified, and appeal items 1-3 on that basis.

Sincerely,
Sai

communications.subject: Delaware Freedom of Information Act Request: Public Records Request - 102 Columbus Drive
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Delaware Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Underground storage tank (UST) and leaking UST (LUST) information for Cartanza Grain Inc. located at 102 Columbus Drive in Dover (facility ID 10152639). Please include the following record types, if available: UST registration/notification forms; UST inspection reports; UST closure documentation; the initial LUST incident report(s); the initial LUST site investigation; quarterly groundwater monitoring reports; remedial action plan(s); remedial action completion report(s); and LUST incident closure/No Further Action (NFA) documentation. Project no. K9407154.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jonathan Rudenberg, a citizen of Delaware, in coordination with Caitlin Downey.

communications.subject: Minnesota Government Data Practices Act Request: GDPA Request: Fusus logs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Minnesota Government Data Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) User manuals, handbooks, or comparable instructional documents provided to the department by Fusus regarding any Fusus product the agency uses.

2) User manuals, handbooks, policies, protocols, or comparable instructional documents developed by the department pertaining to the use of any Fusus product.

3) Audit logs/audit trails documenting each time a department account has accessed live or recorded video footage through the Fusus platforms from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed.

4) Metadata for each Intelligent AI Alert generated by the department's Fusus system from 1/1/2024 until the date this request is processed. Fusus Intelligent AI Alerts automatically notify authorized users when Fusus AI-connected cameras detect pre-defined events (e.g. a fight) or profiles (e.g. a vehicle of interest). Please note that I am not requesting the video footage or any personally identifying information associated with the alert, but rather the metadata. communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: MSNBC Wedding Communication
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All email communications pertaining to the Saturday, November 24 wedding of MSNBC anchors Joe Scarborough and Mika Brzezinski at the National Archives. Please include emails containing references to "Scarborough," "Brzezinski," "Morning Joe," and "MSNBC" sent during the last six months. I am also requesting any official internal documents pertaining to the planning and coordination of the wedding.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Jeremy Barr

communications.subject: Request for More Time
communications.communication:
December 21, 2018 
Jeremy Barr MuckRock News 
DEPT MR 64300 
411A Highland Ave. 
Somerville, MA 02144 

Re: Freedom of Information Act Request NGC19-102 
Dear Mr. Barr: 
You submitted a Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to our office on November 27, 2018 via FOIAonline. We assigned your request the above internal tracking number in addition to your FOIAOnline tracking number NARA-NGC-2019-000134. In your request, you asked for: All email communications pertaining to the Saturday, November 24 wedding of MSNBC anchors Joe Scarborough and Mika Brzezinski at the National Archives. Please include emails containing references to "Scarborough," "Brzezinski," "Morning Joe," and "MSNBC" sent during the last six months. I am also requesting any official internal documents pertaining to the planning and coordination of the wedding. 
Your request falls within the “unusual circumstances” categories contemplated by the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. §552 (a) (6) (B) (iii) (I) (II) and (III), and we need additional time to respond to your request beyond the twenty business days provided by the FOIA statute. We had to reach out to several offices to search for and collect any responsive records, and we need additional time to finish the search and review any search results. In addition, we may have to consult with other offices of the agency that have a substantial interest in the subject matter. 
To enable us to respond more quickly to you, you do have the option to reformulate your request to reduce the amount of time required to complete our search and review, or to arrange an alternative time frame for the processing of this request. 
We regret the necessity of this delay, but assure you that we will process your request as soon as possible. If you have any questions you may contact me. You may also contact our FOIA Public Liaison, Gary M. Stern for assistance at 8601 Adelphi Road, College Park, MD 20740-6002, 301-837-1750, Garym.Stern@nara.gov. 
Sincerely, 
Susan Gillett Government Information Specialist 
Office of General Counsel 
Tel: 301-837-3409 
Email: susan.gillett@nara.gov
